SIMPLE: strand
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Strand
<hw>Strand</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Probably fr. D.
<ets>streen</ets> a skein; akin to G. <ets>str⟦aum⟧hne</ets> a skein,
lock of hair, strand of a rope.]</ety> <def>One of the twists, or
strings, as of fibers, wires, etc., of which a rope is
composed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strand
<hw>Strand</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To break a strand of (a
rope).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Strand
<hw>Strand</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>strand</ets>; akin to D.,
G., Sw., & Dan. <ets>strand</ets>, Icel. <ets>str⟦oum⟧nd</ets>.]</ety>
<def>The shore, especially the beach of a sea, ocean, or large lake;
rarely, the margin of a navigable river.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Strand birds</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<cref>Shore birds</cref>, under <er>Shore</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Strand
plover</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a black-bellied plover. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Plover</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Strand
wolf</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the brown hyena.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Strand
<hw>Strand</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stranded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stranding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To drive on a strand; hence, to
run aground; <as>as, to <ex>strand</ex> a ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Strand
<hw>Strand</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To drift, or be
driven, on shore to run aground; <as>as, the ship <ex>stranded</ex> at
high water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strang</ent>⟦br⟧
